mlb.UBR <- read_csv("/Users/quinyuter/Desktop/Chicago Dogs/mlb.UBR.csv") %>%
  filter(!is.na(UBR))
## Rows: 145 Columns: 23
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (2): last_name, first_name
## dbl (21): player_id, year, ab, pa, hit, single, double, triple, home_run, st...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
## Because the American Association is only 64 games into the season, but the MLB was 100 games in at the time this information was taken, I need to do some simple proportions so that the stats line up. This only really matters for the stats that matter and that compound, aka stats that only increase that can only go up.. 
mlb.UBR <- mlb.UBR %>%
  mutate(across(c(b_rbi, b_total_bases, r_total_stolen_base, b_gnd_into_dp, r_run, ab, pa, single, hit, double, triple, home_run, strikeout, walk, ), function(x) x*(64/100)))
UBR.full <- lm(UBR ~ pa + hit + single + double + triple + batting_avg + slg_percent + b_total_bases + r_total_stolen_base + b_gnd_into_dp + r_run, data = mlb.UBR)
autoplot(UBR.full)

The linearity assumption is broken, so we must transform the predictors

UBR.full2 <- lm(UBR ~ sqrt(pa) + sqrt(hit) + sqrt(single) + sqrt(double) + sqrt(triple) + sqrt(batting_avg) + sqrt(slg_percent) + sqrt(b_total_bases) + sqrt(r_total_stolen_base) + sqrt(b_gnd_into_dp) + sqrt(r_run), data = mlb.UBR)
autoplot(UBR.full2)

The assumptions look much better satisfied, so lets move on.

The subset size with the lowest value bic looks to be just one variable (sqrt(r___)), but that isnt a sufficient enough amount of variables, so I am going to use a 3 variable model. Looking at the summary from earlier, the other model with 3 variables uses the square root of total stolen bases, total runs, and total doubles

bic3 <- lm(UBR ~ sqrt(r_total_stolen_base) + sqrt(double) + sqrt(r_run), data = mlb.UBR)
library(broom)

It looks like both the best subsets BIC model and the backward stepwise regression model are the same. I am choosing them because they have the highest adjusted R-squared value, the lowest AIC value, and the second lowest BIC value. Therefore, we are going to use total stolen bases, runs, and doubles to predict what the UBR would be for our players.

Prediction

First, I am making a dataframe of the team, including their stolen bases, runs, and doubles, and eventually their predicted UBRs. I am also using the same column names as the other data frame for ease of transferring data.

dogs.data <- data.frame(Player = c("Matt Bottcher", "Ryan Lidge", "Dylan Rosa", "David Maberry", "Josh Altmann", "Jesus Lujano", "Luke Mangieri", "Ben Livorsi", "Nick Heath", "Brennan Metzger", "Cody Bohanek", "Payton Eeles", "General McCarthur"), r_total_stolen_base = c(16, 1, 5, 0, 14, 9, 3, 0, 28, 4, 11, 1, 3), r_run = c(49, 41, 36, 12, 45, 28, 33, 14, 41, 27, 29, 5, 5), double = c(14, 11, 14, 7, 15, 10, 13, 4, 6, 7, 5, 1, 0), UBR = 0)

Now, using the data from before, and our players data, to predict their UBR values. I am going to round them to 1 decimal place, since that is how many decimal places are used in MLBs stat

## Matt botcher
dogs.data["1", "UBR"]<- round(predict(UBR.back, data.frame(r_total_stolen_base = 16, r_run = 49, double = 14)), 1)
